<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Characteristic Species</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Ammophila</i> <i>arenaria</i> is dominant in the herbaceous layer. Emergent shrubs may be present at low cover, including <i>Baccharis</i> <i>pilularis</i> or <i>Lupinus</i> <i>arboreus</i>. </div>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Vegetation Layers</h4>
	<div class="text">  Herbs < 1 m; cover is intermittent to continuous. </div>
</div>

        
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Membership Rules</h4>
	<ul class="text">
		
		<li><i>Ammophila arenaria</i> > 80% relative cover in the herbaceous layer (cf. Keeler-Wolf et al. 2003a).</li>
		
		<li><i>Ammophila arenaria</i> is > 60% relative cover in the herbaceous layer (Buck-Diaz et al. 2021, Sikes et al. 2021).</li>
		
	</ul>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Habitats</h4>
	<div class="text"> Dunes of coastal bars, foredunes, river mouths, spits along the immediate coastline. The substrate is sand. The USFWS Wetland Inventory (1996 national list) recognizes <i>Ammophila arenaria</i> as a FACU plant. </div>
</div>

        
