<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Ammophila arenaria </i>is a cool-season, coarse perennial grass with deep, tough creeping rhizomes. It grows well in areas where sand shifts and actively buries plants. It has stout stems up to 90 cm tall and long leaf blades and dense, spike-like panicles of flowers. Seed production is usually low; it mainly spreads vegetatively, including rhizome fragments transported by storm surf. This introduction from Europe has been widely planted on the Atlantic and Pacific coasts of North America to stabilize shifting sand dunes (Apteckar 2000, Pickart and Barbour 2007, Russo et al. 2000). <br/>
<br/>
<i>Ammophila arenaria </i>is now the predominant vegetation type in many dune systems along the Pacific coast from Ventura Co. to British Columbia. Many habitat changes occur with its presence: dune stabilization, alteration of dune morphology, reduction in native stands of the <i>Abronia latifolia-Ambrosia chamissonis, Leymus mollis, </i>and other alliances, and a reduction in habitat for both rare animals (e.g., snowy plover, <i>Charadrius alexandrinus</i>) and rare plants (e.g., <i>Erysimum menziesii </i>ssp. <i>eurekense </i>and <i>Layia carnosa, </i>both CNPS list 1B.1 plants). See Apteckar 2000, Boyd 1992, Pickart and Barbour 2007, and Pickart and Sawyer 1998. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
