    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast</b> (261Af-k). Stands occur from San Mateo Co. south to the Monterey Bay and Morro Bay areas, where they are extensive (Casavecchia and Biondi 2001, Walgren et al. 2005), and to the Guadalupe-Nipomo Dunes, where restoration is active (King 2004).</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast</b> (263Aa-b, Ad-e, Ag-k). Stands are scattered from the Oregon border south to Marin Co. Stands for Bodega Head (Barbour 1970, Danin et al. 1998), the central Humboldt Co. coast (Barbour and Johnson 1977, Duebendorfer 1989, LaBanca 1993, Parker 1974), and Point Reyes National Seashore (Keeler-Wolf et al. 2003a) have <i>Abronia latifolia, Ambrosia chamissonis, Calystegia soldanella, Lathyrus littoralis, </i>and <i>Leymus mollis</i>. Stands along the north spit of Humboldt Bay spread at a rate of 5 ha per year between 1962 and 1989; <i>Ammophila arenaria </i>would continue to invade, spread, and eventually displace the native <i>Leymus</i>-dominated and dune mat vegetation if it had not been managed (Buell et al. 1995). The grass has been removed from near-shore dunes of the Lanphere Dunes unit of the Humboldt Bay National Refuge and other areas on the north spit.  Recently sampled stands in Sonoma County (Klein et al. 2015, Buck-Diaz et al. 2020).</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Coast</b> (261Ba-b, Bh). Stands exist in scattered locations in Santa Barbara Co., including the Purisima Point area of Vandenberg Air Force Base (Schmalzer and Hinkle 1987).  Known stands in the Southern Channel Islands (HDR 2014).</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> In the last two decades, land managers have undertaken significant efforts to restore native dune vegetation through eliminating <i>Ammophila arenaria </i>and other non-native species. Removal of <i>A. arenaria </i>is expensive and time-consuming if the stands are extensive, but successful results have been achieved (Apteckar 2000, Pickart and Sawyer 1998). Many publicly managed lands along the coast are funding its removal, and once removed, native dune vegetation and associated wildlife respond favorably (Rodgers and Adams 2006). Recent efforts have reduced stands substantially in Humboldt, Marin, and Monterey Cos. (J. Rodgers, pers. comm. 2006, A. Pickart 1997, pers. comm. 2007). </div>
</div>

    

    

